OOP'S(object oriented programming structure): language that surrounds near the object. For real world programming we need object oriented programming.

Pure OOPS: all concepts of oops should be followed + using non-primitive data types only
programming language which obeys the above two conditions such programming languages are pure Object oriented.
java does not follow multiple inheritance & hybrid inheritance and using primitive data types like int, float, etc. So we can say that java is not pure object oriented.
Their are some language like 'Ruby' & 'small talk' which are pure object oriented.

Data hiding: our secret data should not go out directly to the outside world.
By using private variables we can hide our data. Now only the authorized person can access that data, which have username and password.

Abstracation: Hiding the internal implementation(internal code) and provide the set of services.
Example: ATM machine, we have various features like check min. balance, withdrawl balance, change PIN, transfer fund.(Services provided)
All these features are implemented using separate function internally
Some advantages of abstraction:
1. Security
2. Maintenance
3. Modularity
To achieve abstraction we use interfaces & abstract class.

Encapsulation: process of binding of variables & methods for security purpose.
Three pillars of security(data hiding, abstraction, encapsulation)

Encapsulation = data hiding + abstraction

Tightly encapsulated class: A class is tightly encapsulated iff all the variables inside that class are declared private.
If parent class is loosly encapsulated then child class obviously become loosely ecpapsulated.

Relationship: provides reusability of code.
There are 2 types of relationships

1. Has - a relationnship: without inheritance we can use any methods of class, but we cannot modifi any method of the class we have to use the method provided as it is.
import java.util.Scanner;
public class A {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);// here Scanner class has a relationship with class A
        int x = sc.nextInt();// here we are using method nextInt() without inheriting the Scanner class
    }
}
One of the disadvantage of has-a relationship is that one class is dependend on another so we have to use that class as it is otherwise not. 

has-a relationship further divided into two categories-
(a) Composition: If we delete container objects there is no chance of existing of contained objects. Strong association b/w contained and container objects.
This strong association has-a relationship is known as composition.
(b) Aggregation: If we delete container objects there maybe chance of existing of contained objects. weak association b/w contained and container objects.
This weak association has-a relationship is known as composition.

2. Is-a relationship(inheritance): reusability of code + reduce dependency
public class A {
    public void m1(){

    }
}
class demo extends A {
// here in demo class we use m1() method as it is or we can also modify it. 
}

has-a relationship further divided into two categories-
single-level inheritance, multi-level inheritance, hierarchical inheritance(possible in java)
multiple & hybrid inheritance is not possible in java

(a) Single-level inheritance: Only two classes are invloved.
class Parent{
    public void m1(){

    }
    public void m2(){

    }
}
class child extends Parent{
    public void m3(){

    }
}
class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Parent p1 = new Parent();
        child c1 = new child();
        Parent p2 = new child();
        child c2 = new Parent();//error: Type mismatch: cannot convert from Parent to child
    }// child class cannot hold parent class
}

(b) multi-level inheritance:
class A{
    public void m1();
}
class B extends A{// class B has 2 methods m2() of its own and m1() inherited 
    public void m2();
}
class C extends B{// class C has 3 methods m3() of its own and m1(), m2() inherited 
    public void m3();
}

(c) hierarchical inheritance: when a parent class has more than 1 child class.
class A{
}
class B extends A{
}
class C extends A{
}

In java by-default inheritance is hierarchical because all classes in java has a mother class which is object class.

(d) multiple inheritance(not supported by java): multiple parents has only 1 child 
why java does not support multiple inheritance with respect to class? due to the ambiguity problem
class A{
    public void m1(){
        System.out.println("123");
    }
}
class B{
    public void m1(){
        System.out.println("234");
    }
}
class C extends A, B{//here we get compile time error
    
}

But with respect to interface multiple-inheritance is possible.
interface A{
    public void m1();
}
interface B{
    public void m1();
}
class C implements A,B{
    public void m1(){
        System.out.println("123");
    }
}
In C++ we can fix the ambiguity problem in multiple inheritance by using the scope resolution operator, but in java we can't have such operator to fix this problem.

Every class inherits the object class.
class A{// this class inherits the object class. A-> object class
}
class B extends A {// this class as-well. B->A->object class
}
Here it is not multiple inheritance because class B extends A and then object class indirectly B extends object class not directly
so indirect multiple inheritance is allowed but direct multiple inheritance is not

cyclic-inheritance is not supported by java.
class A extends B{//The hierarchy of the type A is inconsistent

}
class B extends A{//Cycle detected: a cycle exists in the type hierarchy between B and A
    
}

Hybrid-inheritance is also not supported by java. Due to diamond problem in multiple inheritance it is not allowed.

